Comment: A normal, somewhat aggressive first move.
I generally have bad luck with the Sicilian so I like Open Game.
An interestingly defensive choice of knight movement.  This is more of a waiting move than anything, leading to the dangerous Vienna Game.
Black decides to take the Falkbeer Defense, challenging the d5 square.
White has nailed down the d-pawn by absolutely controlling the d5 square.
Alekhine recommends Nxe4 here - this move is rather timid and not terribly good.
More aggression, White is trying to assert control over the fifth rank.
But White makes a bad blunder there and gets Black's bishop out of the back rank, in a strong and annoying position to boot.
Another, even worse move.  White is apparently trying to attack Black's center.
Black sees the undefended knight and the opportunity to check the king and fork the rook as well.
The most sensible move, White wants that bishop off the board.
Bxd2 or Bxd4 might be good here, but getting a rook off the board on the sixth move is always nice.
White moves to trap the bishop in his corner; not the best move in the world since Qxa1 is available, though it does defend the d-pawn.
More and more captures, leading to a weak White formation.
Prepping for a Bxf7, a really bad move as White should have other priorities.
Castling might work here but Black has nothing to fear from the weak check and will keep harassing White.
White follows through. An attack, finally, although a weak one.
Forced, basically, as Ke7 pins in the queen and is asking for something bad to happen.
An attack on the center, White wants to bolster up his burgeoning attack.
There is more havoc to be wreaked; White's attack is still pretty toothless and Black is having fun here.
